Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Smoke rose approximately 300 agl then had strong SW wind carrying smoke to the Northeast."

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Piles burned down well so lingering light smoke will settle in low areas; specifically warm springs canyon."
Remarks: "Clean piles; consumed very well."

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Smoke rose 300-500 agl then dispersed to the NE."

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Settled into local drainages; most cleared out with the Southwest winds."
"Settled into local drainages very minimal"
"Smoke had a little drift and minimal rise upon ignitions; but dissipated quickly after getting heat built up."

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "1000 FT AGL heading to the N"

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "1000 FT AGL heading to the north east"

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "The smoke rose 100-200 feet and was pushed to the east.  The piles were spread out so the smoke impacts were light to the surrounding area."

Emission Reduction Techniques: "Burn Before Green Up; Backing Fire; Mosaic / Jackpot Burning"
Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Smoke plume followed the primary diurnal influences; of Burnt Canyon.   The forecasted winds were accurate and the smoke moved; toward the N/NE in the morning switching to and moving more toward the E/SE in the afternoon.  The cloud cover in the afternoon kept most of the smoke laying low and hanging more over the burn area and in the Burnt Canyon drainage. During the travel back to the Ranger Station in Camp Verde; I did stop to observe the smoke from HWY 260 in Cottonwood at approximately 1630.  I was unable to see any smoke from the burn unit."
Remarks: "At approximately 1430 cloud cover was approach 100% and the smoke activity decreased due to the rise in relative humidity which hindered the consumption of the finer fuels.  Upon departing the unit  at 1530 cloud cover was at 100%; and the smoke was still light.  It is anticipated that there will be some smoke remaining in the area over the next few days; due to heavier fuels; and some jackpots that are still consuming. There are little to no significant anticipated or expected outside of the burn area."

Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Ignitions were completed for the entire burn area around 1130. Fire behavior was moderate and did not form a distinct column. Smoke drifted off site with the prevalent winds. Some smoke persisted at ground level throughout the day but most rose to about 4000' AGL and drifted north. Smaller wisps occasionally drifted eastward. By 1700 smoke production was greatly diminished. Smoke continued to drift to the north with out impact. Storm cloud and light precipitation over the burn area around 1800 kept smoke closer to ground level which subsequently settled in the Clark Memorial Airport and Camp Civitan area after night fall. Smoke was light and visibility good. Light winds continued to push smoke out of the area during the night leaving only a slight haze due north of the burn area for several miles until sunup. Very light smoke drained into the side of the City of WIlliams but started lifting by 0600."

Emission Reduction Techniques: "Burn More Frequently; Aerial / Mass Ignition; Backing Fire"
Diurnal Plume Characteristics: "Smoke rose approximately 4000'-6000' and dispersed to the east towards Desert View and Cameron.  Surface level winds (eye level) remained in the 2-5 mph range throughout the burn period and overnight.  Moderate smoke impacts were observed at sunset in the inner canyon in the vicinity of the prescribed fire and 1-2 miles upstream/downstream as well as along Desert View Drive.  "
Remarks: "No smoke impacts to Grand Canyon Village.  Tusayan (town) and Grand Canyon airport had minimal smoke impacts overnight and residual smoke cleared by 0800.  Tusayan Ranger Station (USFS) received moderate overnight smoke impacts which cleared out by 0900.  Winds remained steady overnight and began increasing around midnight which cleared the majority of smoke from Desert View Drive and the inner canyon.  NWS predicted steadily increasing winds for the fire area over the next 48 hours so no further ignitions were implemented and all holding resources concentrated on improving lines and bonepiling remaining fuels adjacent to the holding lines."
